{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dbd0024f-9d35-4e6f-b628-b31a80c71ad6","content":"In .NET 10 MAUI, `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` was replaced with a **cross-platform** property. Remove the iOS-specific namespace and use `IgnoreSafeArea` on the page instead:\n\n```xml\n<!-- .NET 9 (old) -->\n<ContentPage\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"\n    ...>\n\n<!-- .NET 10 (new) -->\n<ContentPage\n    xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n    xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\"\n    x:Class=\"MyApp.MainPage\"\n    IgnoreSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- `IgnoreSafeArea=\"False\"` → content stays **inside** safe area (status bar, notch, home indicator). This is what you want.\n- `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` → content extends behind system UI (full-bleed).\n- It's now cross-platform, so it also works on Android (cutouts/navigation bar) — no need for platform-specific namespaces.\n- You can remove the `xmlns:ios` namespace declaration if it was only used for `UseSafeArea`.\n\nIf you need different behavior per-platform, you can still use `OnPlatform`:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage IgnoreSafeArea=\"{OnPlatform iOS=False, Android=True}\" ...>\n```\n\nCheck the [.NET 10 MAUI migration guide](https://learn.microsoft.com/dotnet/maui/migration/) for any additional breaking changes.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"005c1a85-4b61-477d-9f9e-a61f97f8cd1e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI migration issue from .NET 9 to .NET 10 regarding safe area handling on iOS. This is a known breaking change in .NET 10 MAUI.\n\nIn .NET 10, the `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` attached property was removed. The replacement is to use padding or the new safe area APIs.\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. In .NET MAUI for .NET 10 (which would be MAUI 10), there were changes to how safe areas work on iOS. The `UseSafeArea` platform-specific was deprecated/removed, and the recommended approach changed.\n\n\nIn .NET 10, the `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` XAML attribute that was previously available is no longer supported—it was removed as a breaking change. Previously you could declare it in your XAML markup to automatically handle safe area insets on iOS, but now that API is gone and you'll need to handle safe area padding manually or use the newer safe area inset APIs instead. The most likely culprit is that `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` was replaced with a cross-platform `Page.IgnoreSafeArea` property in .NET 10, where setting it to `false` ensures the page respects the safe area and content won't overlap the status bar. Since the user's content is now going behind the status bar, the old platform-specific approach no longer works as expected. In .NET 10, the iOS-specific `UseSafeArea` attribute was removed in favor of a cross-platform `IgnoreSafeArea` property—setting it to `False` respects safe areas and should prevent content from appearing behind the status bar. I should note that the exact API name might vary, so checking the official migration documentation would be wise. The modern approach would be to set padding dynamically to account for safe area insets, though I'm not entirely certain about the exact .NET 10 API since it's still in preview—it likely involves a property like `IgnoreSafeArea` or similar built-in handling on the Page itself.","outputTokens":2121,"requestId":"E82D:2A766B:13EC343:1680267:69F9434A"},"id":"65cc7cb5-6a98-40fb-a0ec-4c82851ab040","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:10:11.641Z","parentId":"5d5ce0f6-043d-4464-afde-db12a67882b2"}
